                            "termSource": null,
                            "termAccession": ""
                        },
                        "description": "Metabolites were identified using the NIST05 mass spectral search and comparison software (National Institute of Standards and Technology, Gaithersburg, MD, USA; http://www.nist.gov/srd/mslist.htm) and the mass spectral and retention time index (RI) collection of the Golm Metabolome Database [1][2]. Mass spectral matching was manually supervised and matches accepted with thresholds of match > 650 (with maximum match equal to 1000) and RI deviation < 1.0 %. RIs were calculated form standard additions to each chromatogram of a mixture of C12, C15, C19, C22, C32, C36 n-alkanes.\n</p>\nRef:</br>\n[1] N. Schauer, D. Steinhauser, S. Strelkov, D. Schomburg, G. Allison, T. Moritz, K. Lundgren, U. Roessner-Tunali, M. G. Forbes, L. Willmitzer, A. R. Fernie and J. Kopka (2005) GC-MS libraries for the rapid identification of metabolites in complex biological samples, FEBS Letters 579: 1332-1337. PMID:15733837</br>\n[2] J. Kopka, N. Schauer, S. Krueger, C. Birkemeyer, B. Usadel, E. Bergmueller, P. Doermann, W. Weckwerth, Y. Gibon, M. Stitt, L. Willmitzer, A. R. Fernie and D. Steinhauser (2005) GMD@CSB.DB: the Golm Metabolome Database, Bioinformatics 21: 1635-1638. PMID:15613389</br>",
